20. I know it's tough rn, but please stick around, because I guarantee you, it'll be worth it.

rektguys are down bad, but we'll never die. https://t.co/SnC6guOnz4

19. Trust me when I say this, if you can survive and live through this price action, you will come out on the other side stronger than you'd ever have imagined...not just as a trader but also as a human.
18. If you're new, you might look up to certain OGs, because "they've been through it" or "they've seen it all". Well, now's your turn to become an OG.

17. IMO, communities that form during these times hit a different level of strength and resilience, and that's gonna be us. Coz you can bet your arse that @greatmando_nft  and I aren't going anywhere. We've been through this before, multiple times, and we'll do it again.

16. Remember, literally ALL of us are rekt rn...we're all rektguys. This Discord is designed to be a community where we can support each other and empathetically make light of the situation, because we're all hurting bad.

15. This is a message I wrote to our @rektguyNFT and @DegenzNFT community this morning in our Discord, so if you don't care about this projects you don't have to keep reading, but I'm going to carry on with what I wrote because it translates to other communities too.

14. Take it out, and remember to be disciplined about taking profits next time. If you have capital, be disciplined about adding, dollar-cost average, and don't use all your chips in one go. It doesn't matter if you've made a mistake, what matters is if you can learn from it.

13...and if I had IRL requirements I'd probably be selling. The point I'm trying to make here is that if you have to be honest with yourself. I'd strongly recommend budgeting, and devising a strategy. How much do you need IRL?

12. However, I've made sure I've taken enough cash out for IRL needs to not have to worry if it keeps going lower and be able to add. That's not to brag, but it's to raise an important point that if I WASN'T in this situation, I wouldn't be buying...

11. We're at a point of massive uncertainty, and no one should be gambling with money they can't afford to lose. I've been writing for weeks about dollar-cost-averaging and I fully believe that's the right strategy and people will make fortunes from it.

10...and at some point in time we'll start hearing bull cases and the paradigm will shift. So it now comes down to your personal situation. If you are over-extended or need the money for IRL stuff, in debt etc...then you should sell.

9. They always do. I can't tell you what the exact solution is here, and I can't tell you how long it will take, and I'm certainly not calling it a bottom, but I am telling you that although history never repeats itself, it certainly rhymes...

8. An unknown disease, complete uncertainty, the entire economy SHUT DOWN. Yet, if you sold in March 2020, that would have been one of the worst sales in history...because guess what...humans figured it out.

7. But for every bad reason, there is also a good reason, and it just takes a bit of time and patience for it to come. Just think about March 2020...it literally felt like the world was going to end at some points.

6...every time, in the next year or two later, we saw new highs. "But this time is different." Is it? Let me tell you, every few years, there is ALWAYS going to be ANOTHER new reason for markets to go lower. That's just how it works.

5...You can pull up a 100Y S&P500 chart and zoom out and think "omg we have so much lower to go", but that is a fool's game. You could have done that in 2008, in 2011, in 2013, in 2016, in 2018 and in 2020...and guess what...
4. The market goes in cyclical, we go down, and we go up, but the long-term trend over an expanded period of time is up...because guess what? The world progresses, grows and becomes more efficient...

3. ...hence the market is understandably throwing a tantrum. This is only my second crypto cycle, but probably like my 5th or 6th real market cycle, and let me tell you something, it's always the same story over and over again.

12. To summarise, I have very mixed feelings. I think he's played an absolute blinder here and there are certainly arguments on both sides of the coin. I would end it with, if I was an mfer holder, I'd be feeling both charmed and disappointed rn. https://t.co/0TgEmsOiIY

11. I've yet to see a truly successful "community takeover" of a project and believe you need a core team spearheading it for it to have real success. I do wish the partial new owners of this project all the best and hope they can buck that trend and make this a good one.

10. When someone else makes a lot of money, it's human reaction to criticise it. We all do it. We also like to see people visibly working hard at stuff to justify the money they've made. But ultimately, "work smart not hard" is certainly a concept.

9. If that OE has value or utility further down the line then I shall certainly eat my words and that would honestly be amazing to see (afterall even I minted one because I felt I "had" to...so IDK why I'm complaining about this lol).

8. I think the fact that he retains 25% of the royalties is ok, because it's his art and he does deserve something in perpetuity IMO. The bit that I don't love is the OE which he made another 1.2K ETH out of and walks away with...kinda leaves a bad taste in my mouth.

7. But personally, I couldn't do it. If I made THAT much money as a result of my creation, but also because of relentless community support, I'd feel very indebted and want to give my everything to build out the project or commit funds to that effect.

6. Is there anything wrong with that? Absolutely not. It's art. Performance art actually. It was an unbelievably smart idea and he played a blinder...it's actually very impressive to see and I think he understood and utilised the power of web3 extremely well.

5. 38.8K ETH in YTD volume which translates to 970ETH in trading fees, on top of the 690ETH that was made on the initial sale. He also made an additional 1.2K ETH on this open edition, so that totals 2860ETH which is $5m at today's levels of ETH. Quite a lot.
4. I think it's easy enough to say "I haven't promised anything" but it's worth noting that he did make a lot of money out of this, as a result of the community's strength, perseverance and love.

3. It was SO relatable, that it ended up being a huge hit this year, and a community formed organically without sartoshi really having to do much. It arguably became bigger than sartoshi himself, but it was something that HE created and he is owed a lot of respect in that regard.
